                        <decoDesc>
                            <decoNote type="illustration">Four miniatures, including one double-page
                                miniature, in a style typical of a Bukhara manuscript of the second
                                half of the sixteenth century. </decoNote>
                            <decoNote type="decoration">Margins are richly decorated with
                                stencil designs in various colours picked out in gold, or with
                                arabesque medallions of different coloured paper inlaid among floral
                                scrolls or flecks of gold. Illuminated heading on folio <locus
                                    from="1b" to="1b">1b</locus>.</decoNote>
                        </decoDesc>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <decoNote>Fairly modern oriental binding of red leather with sunk
                                medallions, pendants and corner-pieces (rebacked and the top edges
                                repaired).</decoNote>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <origDate calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1550" notAfter="1600">circa
                                1560</origDate>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The colophon on folio <locus from="19b" to="19b">19b</locus> has been
                                covered with thick blue paint.</p>
                            <p>Formerly the property of William Oliver (d. 1847), of the
                                East India Company, who was on the Council Board of the
                                Madras government before his retirement in 1836. He was also a
                                Fellow of the Royal Asiatic Society. The manuscript was then passed
                                on to <persName type="standard"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/120696480"
                                    key="person_120696480">Adam Clarke</persName>. On the front fly-leaf is written:
                                'To the Revd. A. Clarke LL.D. with W. Oliver's respectful Compts.
                                1810'. This is followed by a line of Persian and the initials W*O
                                (William Oliver), an indecipherable octagonal seal and the title of
                                the work written twice in Persian. The manuscript was later acquired
                                by the Persian scholar <persName type="standard"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/#Bland,_Nathaniel,_1803-1865"
                                    key="person_20108923">Nathaniel Bland (1803-1865)</persName>.
                                Bland’s oriental manuscripts were sold through Bernard Quaritch in
                                1866 to <persName type="standard"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/#Crawford,_Alexander_Crawford_Lindsay,_Earl_of,_1812-1880"
                                    key="person_97751058">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of
                                    Crawford</persName>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Purchased by Enriqueta Rylands, on behalf of the John Rylands
                                Library, in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from
                                    <persName type="standard"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/#Crawford,_James_Ludovic_Lindsay,_Earl_of,_1847-1913"
                                    key="person_9985420">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of
                                    Crawford</persName>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
